{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d5562ea7-8189-461f-93a7-323306650a40","content":"Here's a step-by-step approach:\n\n### 1. Get into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternate: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\n\nThis gives live CPU/GC/threadpool stats without a full trace.\n\n### Tips for Windows containers\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available, download the standalone `dotnet-trace` from the [.NET diagnostics releases](https://github.com/dotnet/diagnostics).\n- Copy the `.nettrace` file out with:\n  ```bash\n  kubectl cp <pod-name>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n  ```\n- If the container lacks the SDK, you can sidecar the tools or use **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar for remote collection without modifying the app container.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e5719cac-093d-49ce-a054-458849382964","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":446,"requestId":"C3C9:86E8:1CC68CC:2056E67:6A07C182"},"id":"c409dd75-3316-4594-810d-83c2e20e91fc","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:59:57.368Z","parentId":"6fbddb6c-8a0b-4bb9-967a-baf5b417f223"}
